From fc216b76fcc1d9ea72f90d8a30f38664dca2e8e4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Thomas Grainger <tagrain@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0100
Subject: [PATCH] tcp: reset the connection on a valid RST at rcv_nxt under a
 delayed ACK

Radar / Feedback: FB23590387

RFC 5961 Section 3.2 requires a RST with SEG.SEQ == RCV.NXT to reset the
connection. In tcp_input(), the RST-validation block tests the exact-match
reset condition against last_ack_sent (and last_ack_sent - 1) instead of
rcv_nxt, and anchors the acceptance window's right edge on
last_ack_sent + rcv_wnd.

When the receiver has delayed-ACKed data (rcv_nxt > last_ack_sent), a valid
RST at rcv_nxt -- which is exactly what a correct peer sends (SND.NXT) -- is
either answered with a challenge ACK instead of resetting, silently dropped
once rcv_wnd has shrunk below the delayed-ACK gap, or (when rcv_wnd == 0)
rejected by the zero-window exact-match arm. Either way the connection is left
ESTABLISHED (half-open): the peer that sent the RST has already fully closed,
so nothing retransmits it. EVFILT_READ never fires, SO_ERROR == 0, and
recv(..., MSG_PEEK) returns EAGAIN.

This is the more severe variant of the same defect present across the BSDs:
XNU accepts only last_ack_sent / last_ack_sent - 1 (never rcv_nxt) and, unlike
FreeBSD, has no net.inet.tcp.insecure_rst escape hatch. OpenBSD (tcp_input.c
rev 1.194, 2005; markus) and NetBSD (rev 1.296, 2009; christos) both fixed the
same delayed-ACK RST failure by anchoring RST validation on rcv_nxt.

Fix: accept a RST at rcv_nxt as an exact match wherever last_ack_sent is
accepted (the in-window reset test and the zero-window/closing-state arm), and
anchor the acceptance window's right edge on rcv_nxt + rcv_wnd. This is the
RFC 5961-mandated point and does not weaken the anti-spoofing intent: an
off-path attacker must still guess rcv_nxt (or last_ack_sent) exactly;
in-window but non-exact RSTs continue to draw a challenge ACK.

Each of the three sub-cases is covered by a deterministic packetdrill
regression test, verified red/green on FreeBSD 15.1 GENERIC kernels under
QEMU/KVM (the same tcp_input.c lineage): a kernel with only the first two
changes still fails the zero-window case (RST at rcv_nxt, rcv_wnd == 0, delayed
ACK) with read() returning EAGAIN instead of ECONNRESET; adding the third
change makes all three pass.

Reproducer (libc only, raw kqueue/kevent + sockets), reproduces on macOS at up
to ~28-46% of connections on macOS 26, and natively on FreeBSD 15.1 at
~1 in 33k, never on Linux:
https://github.com/graingert/asyncio-macos-loopback-rst-hang (c/repro.c)

Also reported: FreeBSD bug 296594; CPython python/cpython#153117 (asyncio's
call_soon-deferred close makes it surface as a silent hang).
---
 bsd/netinet/tcp_input.c | 8 +++++---
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/bsd/netinet/tcp_input.c b/bsd/netinet/tcp_input.c
index b283c3b..1ce2d8f 100644
--- a/bsd/netinet/tcp_input.c
+++ b/bsd/netinet/tcp_input.c
@@ -4475,11 +4475,13 @@ trimthenstep6:
 	 */
 	if (thflags & TH_RST) {
 		if ((SEQ_GEQ(th->th_seq, tp->last_ack_sent) &&
-		    SEQ_LT(th->th_seq, tp->last_ack_sent + tp->rcv_wnd)) ||
+		    SEQ_LT(th->th_seq, tp->rcv_nxt + tp->rcv_wnd)) ||
 		    ((tp->rcv_wnd == 0 || tp->t_state >= TCPS_CLOSE_WAIT) &&
 		    ((tp->last_ack_sent == th->th_seq) ||
-		    (tp->last_ack_sent - 1 == th->th_seq)))) {
-			if (tp->last_ack_sent == th->th_seq || tp->last_ack_sent - 1 == th->th_seq) {
+		    (tp->last_ack_sent - 1 == th->th_seq) ||
+		    (tp->rcv_nxt == th->th_seq)))) {
+			if (tp->last_ack_sent == th->th_seq || tp->last_ack_sent - 1 == th->th_seq ||
+			    tp->rcv_nxt == th->th_seq) {
 				switch (tp->t_state) {
 				case TCPS_SYN_RECEIVED:
 					IF_TCP_STATINC(ifp, rstinsynrcv);
